\begin_layout Title
When functions have no value(s):
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Delta functions and distributions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Steven G.
 Johnson, MIT course 18.303 notes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
These notes give a brief introduction to the motivations, concepts, and
 properties of 
\emph on
distributions
\emph default
, which generalize the notion of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 to allow derivatives of discontinuities, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

delta
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 functions, and other nice things.
 This generalization is increasingly important the more you work with linear
 PDEs, as we do in 18.303.
 For example, Green's functions are extremely cumbersome if one does not
 allow delta functions.
 Moreover, solving PDEs with functions that are not classically differentiable
 is of great practical importance (e.g.
 a plucked string with a triangle shape is not twice differentiable, making
 the wave equation problematic with traditional functions).
 Any serious work with PDEs will eventually run into the concept of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

weak solution,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 which is essentially a version of the distribution concept.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
What's wrong with functions?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most familiar notion of a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 is a map from real numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 to real numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 (or maybe complex numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

); that is, for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 you have a value 
\begin_inset Formula $y=f(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Of course, you may know that one can define functions from any set to any
 other set, but at first glance it seems that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 functions (and multi-dimensional generalizations thereof) are the best-suited
 concept for describing most physical quantities—for example, velocity as
 a function of time, or pressure or density as a function of position in
 a fluid, and so on.
 Unfortunately, such functions have some severe drawbacks that, eventually,
 lead them to be replaced in some contexts by another concept: 
\emph on
distributions
\emph default
 (also called 
\emph on
generalized functions
\emph default
).
 What are these drawbacks?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
No delta functions
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:No-delta-functions"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For lots of applications, such as those involving PDEs and Green's functions,
 one would like to have a function 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(x)$
\end_inset

 whose integral is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

concentrated
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

.
 That is, one would like the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(x)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $x\neq0$
\end_inset

, but with 
\begin_inset Formula $\int\delta(x)dx=1$
\end_inset

 for any integration region that includes 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

; this concept is called a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Dirac delta function
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or simply a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

delta function.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(x)$
\end_inset

 is usually the simplest right-hand-side for which to solve differential
 equations, yielding a Green's function.
 It is also the simplest way to consider physical effects that are concentrated
 within very small volumes or times, for which you don't actually want to
 worry about the microscopic details in this volume—for example, think of
 the concepts of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

point charge,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

point mass,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 a force plucking a string at 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

one point,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

kick
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

suddenly
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 imparts some momentum to an object, and so on.
 The problem is that there is no classical function 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(x)$
\end_inset

 having these properties.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, one could imagine constructing this function as the limit:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta(x)=\lim_{\Delta x\to0^{+}}\begin{cases}
\frac{1}{\Delta x} & 0\leq x<\Delta x\\
0 & \mbox{otherwise}
\end{cases}=\lim_{\Delta x\to0^{+}}\delta_{\Delta x}(x)?
\]

\end_inset

For any 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x>0$
\end_inset

, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\Delta x}(x)$
\end_inset

 at right has integral 
\begin_inset Formula $=1$
\end_inset

 and is zero except near 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

.
 Unfortunately, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x\to0$
\end_inset

 limit does not exist as an ordinary function: 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\Delta x}(x)$
\end_inset

 approaches 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

, but of course 
\begin_inset Formula $\infty$
\end_inset

 is not a real number.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Informally, one often sees 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

definitions
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(x)$
\end_inset

 that describe it as some mysterious object that is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

not quite
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 a function, which 
\begin_inset Formula $=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\neq0$
\end_inset

 but is undefined at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

, and which is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

only really defined inside an integral
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (where it 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

integrates
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to 1).
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Historically, this unsatisfactory description is precisely how 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(x)$
\end_inset

 first appeared, and for many years there was a corresponding cloud of guilt
 and uncertainty surrounding any usage of it.
 Most famously, an informal 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(x)$
\end_inset

 notion was popularized by physicist Paul
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Dirac, who in his 
\emph on
Principles of Quantum Mechanics
\emph default
 (1930) wrote: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(x)$
\end_inset

 is not a quantity which can be generally used in mathematical analysis
 like an ordinary function, but its use must be confined to certain simple
 types of expression for which it is obvious that no inconsistency can arise.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 You know you are on shaky ground, in mathematics, when you are forced to
 appeal to the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

obvious.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 This may leave you with a queasy feeling that 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(x)$
\end_inset

 is somehow not real or rigorous (and therefore anything based on it may
 be suspect).
 For example, integration is an operation that is classically only defined
 for ordinary functions, so it may not even be clear (yet) what 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\int$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 means when we write 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\int\delta(x)dx$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Not all functions are differentiable
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most physical laws can be written in the form of derivatives, but lots of
 functions are not differentiable.
 Discontinuous functions arise all of the time at the interface between
 two materials (e.g.
 think of the density at the interface between glass and air).
 Of course, at a microscopic level you could argue that the quantum wavefunction
s might be continuous, but one hardly wishes to resort to atoms and quantum
 mechanics every time a material has a boundary!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The classic example of a discontinuous function is the Heaviside step function:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S(x)=\begin{cases}
1 & x\geq0\\
0 & x<0
\end{cases}.
\]

\end_inset

The derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $S'(x)$
\end_inset

 is zero everywhere except at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

, where the derivative does not exist—the slope at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

infinity.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $S'(x)$
\end_inset

 very much resembles 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(x)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\infty}^{x}\delta(x')dx'$
\end_inset

 would certainly look something like 
\begin_inset Formula $S(x)$
\end_inset

 if it existed (since the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

integral
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 should be 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x>0$
\end_inset

)—this is not a coincidence, and it would be a shame not to exploit it!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A function doesn't need to be discontinuous to lack a derivative.
 Consider the function 
\begin_inset Formula $|x|$
\end_inset

: its derivative is +1 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x<0$
\end_inset

, but at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 the derivative doesn't exist.
 We say that 
\begin_inset Formula $|x|$
\end_inset

 is only 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

piecewise
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 differentiable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $S(x)$
\end_inset

 is very useful for writing down all sorts of functions with discontinuities.
 
\begin_inset Formula $|x|=xS(x)-xS(-x)$
\end_inset

, for example, and the 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\Delta x}(x)$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

box
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 function on the right-hand-side of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(x)$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

definition
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 above can be written 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\Delta x}(x)=[S(x)-S(x-\Delta x)]/\Delta x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Nagging worries about
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

discrepancies at isolated points
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Continual-worrying-about"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When we try to do linear algebra with functions, we continually find ourselves
 worrying about excluding odd caveats and counterexamples that have to do
 with 
\emph on
finite 
\emph default
discrepancies at isolated points.
 For example, a Fourier series of a square-integrable function converges
 everywhere\SpecialChar ldots
except at isolated points of discontinuity [like the point 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $S(x)$
\end_inset

, where a Fourier series would converge to 0.5].
 As another example, 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle u,v\rangle=\int\bar{u}v$
\end_inset

 defines an inner product on functions and a norm 
\begin_inset Formula $\Vert u\Vert^{2}=\langle u,u\rangle>0$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $u\neq0$
\end_inset

\SpecialChar ldots
except for 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)$
\end_inset

 that are only nonzero for isolated points.
 And with functions like 
\begin_inset Formula $S(x)$
\end_inset

 there are all sorts of apparently pointless questions about what value
 to assign exactly at the discontinuity.
 It may likewise seem odd to care about what value to assign the slope of
 
\begin_inset Formula $|x|$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

; surely any value in 
\begin_inset Formula $[-1,1]$
\end_inset

 should do?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Limits and derivatives
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

cannot always be interchanged
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In numerical and analytical PDE methods, we are continually writing functions
 as limits.
 A Fourier series is a limit as the number of terms goes to infinity.
 A finite-difference method solves the problem in the limit as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x\to0$
\end_inset

.
 We initially find the Green's function as the limit of the response to
 a box-like function that is nonzero outside of a width 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x$
\end_inset

, and then take the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x\to0$
\end_inset

.
 After all of these kinds of things, we eventually substitute our solution
 back into the PDE, and we assume that the limit of the solution is still
 a solution.
 In doing so, however, we usually end up interchanging the limits and the
 differentiation.
 For example, we usually differentiate a Fourier series by: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{dx}\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}a_{n}\sin(n\pi x)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}a_{n}\frac{d}{dx}\sin(n\pi x)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}n\pi a_{n}\cos(n\pi x),
\]

\end_inset

but this 
\emph on
is not always true
\emph default
 if we interpret 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

=
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the usual sense of being true for every 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 The general problem is that 
\emph on
one cannot always interchange limits and derivatives
\emph default
, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d}{dx}\lim\neq\lim\frac{d}{dx}$
\end_inset

.
 (Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}$
\end_inset

 is really a limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{N\to\infty}\sum_{n=1}^{N}$
\end_inset

.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A simple example of this is the function 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{\epsilon}(x)=\begin{cases}
-\epsilon & x<-\epsilon\\
x & -\epsilon\leq x\leq\epsilon\\
\epsilon & x>\epsilon
\end{cases},\qquad f'_{\epsilon}(x)=\begin{cases}
1 & -\epsilon<x<\epsilon\\
0 & |x|>\epsilon
\end{cases}.
\]

\end_inset

The limit as 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon\to0$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\epsilon}(x)$
\end_inset

 is simply zero.
 But 
\begin_inset Formula $f'_{\epsilon}(0)=1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=\left.\frac{d}{dx}\left(\lim_{\epsilon\to0}f_{\epsilon}\right)\right|_{x=0}\neq1=\lim_{\epsilon\to0}\left(\left.\frac{d}{dx}f_{\epsilon}\right|_{x=0}\right).
\]

\end_inset

Notice, however, that this mismatch only occurs at one isolated point 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

.
 The same thing happens for Fourier series: differentiation term-by-term
 works 
\emph on
except at isolated points
\emph default
.
 Thus, this problem returns to the complaint in the previous section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Continual-worrying-about"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection

\emph on
Too much information
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Too-much-information"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 gives us a value at 
\emph on
every point
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, but does this really correspond to a measurable quantity in the physical
 universe? How would you measure the velocity at one 
\emph on
instant
\emph default
 in time, or the density at one 
\emph on
point
\emph default
 in a fluid? Of course, your measurement device could be very precise, and
 very small, and very fast, but in the end 
\emph on
all you can ever measure are averages
\emph default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 over a small region of space and/or time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But an average is the same thing as an integral 
\begin_inset Formula $\int f(x)$
\end_inset

 over the averaging region.
 More generally, instead of averaging 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 uniformly in some region, we could average with some weights 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)$
\end_inset

 (e.g.
 our device could be more sensitive to some points than others).
 Thus, the 
\emph on
only physical question we can ever ask about a function is the value of
 an integral
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}f(x)\phi(x)dx
\]

\end_inset

of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 against a 
\emph on
test function
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But if all we can ever ask is such an integral, why are we worrying about
 isolated points? In fact, why do we even 
\emph on
define
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 to have values at points at all? In a physical application of mathematics,
 perhaps we should only define things that we can measure! This insight
 fixes 
\emph on
every one of the problems above
\emph default
, and leads to the concept of 
\series bold
distributions
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Distributions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The old kind of function is a map from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

: given an 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, we get a value 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Following section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Too-much-information"

\end_inset

, this is too much information; we can only ask for an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

average
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 value given some weight function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)$
\end_inset

.
 So, we make a new definition of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

function
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 that provides this information, and 
\emph on
only
\emph default
 this information: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a rule that given any 
\emph on
test function
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)$
\end_inset

 returns a 
\emph on
number
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $f\{\phi\}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Many authors use the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle f,\phi\rangle$
\end_inset

 instead of 
\begin_inset Formula $f\{\phi\}$
\end_inset

, but we are already using 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle\cdot,\cdot\rangle$
\end_inset

 for inner products and I don't want to confuse matters.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This new definition of a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

function
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is called a 
\series bold
distribution
\series default
 or a 
\series bold
generalized function
\series default
.
 We are no longer allowed to ask the value at a 
\emph on
point
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 This will fix all of the problems with the old functions from above.
 However, we should be more precise about our definition.
 First, we have to specify what 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)$
\end_inset

 can be:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)$
\end_inset

 is an ordinary function 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 (not a distribution) in some set 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

.
 We require 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)$
\end_inset

 to be 
\emph on
infinitely differentiable
\emph default
.
 We also require 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)$
\end_inset

 to be 
\emph on
nonzero
\emph default
 only in some finite region (the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

support
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

): 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is a smooth 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

bump
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 function.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Alternatively, one sometimes loosens this requirement to merely say that
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)$
\end_inset

 must 
\begin_inset Formula $\to0$
\end_inset

 quickly as 
\begin_inset Formula $x\to\pm\infty$
\end_inset

, and in particular that 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}\phi(x)\to0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $x\to\pm\infty$
\end_inset

 for all integers 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[The generalization to functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{x}\in\mathbb{R}^{d}$
\end_inset

, with the distributions corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

-dimensional integrals, is very straightforward, but we will stick to 
\begin_inset Formula $d=1$
\end_inset

 for simplicity.] Second,
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
There is also a third requirement: 
\begin_inset Formula $f\{\phi\}$
\end_inset

 must be continuous, in that if you change 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)$
\end_inset

 continuously the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $f\{\phi\}$
\end_inset

 must change continuously.
 In practice, you will never violate this condition unless you are trying
 to construct perverse counter-examples.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 we require that 
\begin_inset Formula $f\{\phi\}$
\end_inset

 act like integration in that it must be 
\emph on
linear
\emph default
:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $f\{\alpha\phi_{1}+\beta\phi_{2}\}=\alpha f\{\phi_{1}\}+\beta f\{\phi_{2}\}$
\end_inset

 for any numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and any 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{1},\phi_{2}\in\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a linear map from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, and the set of all distributions for a given set of test functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

 is sometimes denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{D}'$
\end_inset

.
 There are two classes of distributions: 
\series bold
regular
\series default
 and 
\series bold
singular
\series default
 distributions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Regular distributions
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

from ordinary functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most obvious way to define a distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $f\{\phi\}$
\end_inset

 is simply an ordinary integral of an ordinary function: given an ordinary
 function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

, we can define the distribution: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boxed{f\{\phi\}=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}f(x)\phi(x)dx}.
\]

\end_inset

This is called a 
\series bold
regular distribution
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Not all ordinary functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 define regular distributions: we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\int f\phi$
\end_inset

 finite for all 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\in\mathcal{D}$
\end_inset

.
 This reduces to requiring that 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{a}^{b}|f(x)|dx<\infty$
\end_inset

 for all intervals 
\begin_inset Formula $[a,b]$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

locally integrable
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Singular distributions
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

& the delta function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although the integral of an ordinary function is 
\emph on
one
\emph default
 way to define a distribution, it is not the 
\emph on
only
\emph default
 way.
 For example, the following distribution is a perfectly good one: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boxed{\delta\{\phi\}=\phi(0)}.
\]

\end_inset

This rule is linear and continuous, there are no weird infinities, nor is
 there anything spooky or non-rigorous.
 Given a test function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(x)$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
distribution
\emph default
 is simply the rule that gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(0)$
\end_inset

 from each 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi.$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(x)$
\end_inset

, however, does not correspond to any ordinary function—it is not a regular
 distribution—so we call it a 
\series bold
singular distribution
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Notation: when we write 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\int\delta(x)\phi(x)dx$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 we don't mean an ordinary integral, we really mean 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\{\phi\}=\phi(0)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Furthermore, when we say 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $f=\delta(x-x')$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 we just mean the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $f\{\phi\}=\phi(x')$
\end_inset

.
 (This kind of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

abuse
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of notation is too convenient, and too widespread, to discard in the name
 of purity.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we look at the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

finite-
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x$
\end_inset

 delta
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 approximation 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\Delta x}(x)$
\end_inset

 from section
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:No-delta-functions"

\end_inset

, that defines the 
\emph on
regular
\emph default
 distribution: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta_{\Delta x}\{\phi\}=\frac{1}{\Delta x}\int_{0}^{\Delta x}\phi(x)dx,
\]

\end_inset

which is just the average of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,\Delta x]$
\end_inset

.
 Now, however, viewed as a distribution, the limit 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x\to0$
\end_inset

 is perfectly well defined:
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We have used the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)$
\end_inset

 is required to be continuous, from which one can show that nothing weird
 can happen with the average of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x\to0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{\Delta x\to0}\delta_{\Delta x}\{\phi\}=\phi(0)=\delta\{\phi\}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\Delta x}\to\delta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Of course, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 distribution is not the only singular distribution, but it is the most
 famous one (and the one from which many other singular distributions are
 built).
 We will see more examples later.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Derivatives of distributions
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

& differentiating discontinuities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How do we define the derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $f'$
\end_inset

 of a distribution? Well, at the very least we want it to be the same as
 the ordinary derivative when 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a regular distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 that happens to be differentiable in the ordinary sense.
 In that case, 
\begin_inset Formula $f'\{\phi\}=\int f'(x)\phi(x)dx=-\int f(x)\phi'(x)dx=f\{-\phi'\}$
\end_inset

, where we have integrated by parts and used the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)$
\end_inset

 is zero outside a finite region to eliminate the boundary terms.
 This is such a nice result that we will use it to 
\emph on
define
\emph default
 the derivative of 
\emph on
any
\emph default
 distribution:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The
\series bold
 distributional derivative
\series default
 
\begin_inset Formula $f'$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $f\{\phi\}$
\end_inset

 is given by the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\boxed{f'\{\phi\}=f\{-\phi'\}}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi'(x)$
\end_inset

 is the ordinary derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(This is sometimes also called a 
\series bold
weak derivative
\series default
.) Since the test functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)$
\end_inset

 were required to be infinitely differentiable, we have a remarkable consequence
: 
\emph on
every distribution is infinitely differentiable
\emph default
 (in the distributional sense).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\{\phi\}=\phi(0)$
\end_inset

, it immediately follows that the derivative of a delta function is the
 distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta'\{\phi\}=\delta\{-\phi'\}=-\phi'(0)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The most important consequence of this definition is that even 
\series bold
discontinuous functions are differentiable
\series default
 as distributions, and their derivatives 
\series bold
give delta functions
\series default
 for each discontinuity.
 Consider the regular distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 defined by the step function 
\begin_inset Formula $S(x)$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S\{\phi\}=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}S(x)\phi(x)dx=\int_{0}^{\infty}\phi(x)dx.
\]

\end_inset

It immediately follows that the distributional derivative of the step function
 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
S'\{\phi\} & = & S\{-\phi'\}=-\int_{0}^{\infty}\phi'(x)dx=\left.-\phi(x)\right|_{0}^{\infty}\\
 & = & \phi(0)-\cancel{\phi(\infty)}=\phi(0).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

But this is exactly the same as 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\{\phi\}$
\end_inset

, so we immediately conclude: 
\begin_inset Formula $\boxed{S'=\delta}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since any function with jump discontinuities can be written in terms of
 
\begin_inset Formula $S(x)$
\end_inset

, we find that the derivative of any jump discontinuity gives a delta function
 multiplied by the magnitude of the jump.
 For example, consider: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=\begin{cases}
x^{2} & x<3\\
x^{3} & x\geq3
\end{cases}=x^{2}+(x^{3}-x^{2})S(x-3).
\]

\end_inset

The distributional derivative works just like the ordinary derivative, except
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $S'=\delta$
\end_inset

, so
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
I'm being a bit glib here.
 How do we know that the product rule works the same? Below, we will rigorously
 define what it means to multiply a distribution by a smooth function like
 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{3}-x^{2}$
\end_inset

, and the ordinary product rule will follow.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{alignedat}{1}f'(x) & =2x+(3x^{2}-2x)S(x-3)+(3^{3}-3^{2})\delta(x-3)\\
 & =18\delta(x-3)+\begin{cases}
2x & x<3\\
3x^{2} & x\geq3
\end{cases},
\end{alignedat}
\]

\end_inset

where of course by 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(x)$
\end_inset

 I mean the distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $f'\{\phi\}$
\end_inset

.
 It is common to be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

casual
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 with notation in this way for distributions, treating them like ordinary
 functions, but you have to remember that you can't evaluate them at any
 point 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, you can only evaluate them for test functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Isolated points
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With ordinary functions, we had to make lots of caveats about isolated points.
 No more with distributions.
 The key point is that two 
\emph on
different
\emph default
 ordinary functions can define the 
\emph on
same
\emph default
 distribution.
 Consider, for example, the function 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f(x)=\begin{cases}
1 & x=0\\
0 & \mbox{otherwise}
\end{cases}.
\]

\end_inset

This is 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 a delta function: it is finite at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

, and is a perfectly acceptable function.
 It also defines a regular distribution: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f\{\phi\}=\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}f(x)\phi(x)dx=0.
\]

\end_inset

Think about it: no matter what 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)$
\end_inset

 is, the integral must give zero because it is only nonzero (by a 
\emph on
finite
\emph default
 amount) at a single point, with zero area (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

zero measure
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for the pure-math folks).
 Thus, in the distribution sense, we can say perfectly rigorously that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f=0
\]

\end_inset

even though 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)\neq0$
\end_inset

 in the ordinary-function sense!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In general, any two ordinary functions that only differ (by 
\emph on
finite
\emph default
 amounts—not delta functions!) at 
\emph on
isolated points
\emph default
 (a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

set of measure zero
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) define the 
\emph on
same 
\emph default
regular distribution.
 We no longer have to make caveats about isolated points—finite values at
 isolated points make 
\emph on
no difference
\emph default
 to a distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, there are no more caveats about the Fourier series or Fourier
 transforms: they converge, period, for distributions.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Technically, we have to choose distributions with the right set of test
 functions.
 The right test functions for the general Fourier transform on the real
 line are those for which 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}\phi(x)\to0$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $x\to\pm\infty$
\end_inset

 for any 
\begin_inset Formula $n>0$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)$
\end_inset

 vanishes faster than any polynomial.
 The resulting distributions are called 
\emph on
tempered distributions
\emph default
, and are the domain of the Fourier transform.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Also, there is no more quibbling about the value of things like 
\begin_inset Formula $S(x)$
\end_inset

 right at the point of discontinuities.
 It doesn't matter, for distributions.
 Nor is there quibbling about the derivative of things like 
\begin_inset Formula $|x|$
\end_inset

 right at the point of the slope discontinuity.
 It is an easy matter to show that the distributional derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $|x|$
\end_inset

 is simply 
\begin_inset Formula $2S(x)-1$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 it is the regular distribution corresponding to the function that is 
\begin_inset Formula $+1$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x<0$
\end_inset

 (with the value at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 being rigorously irrelevant).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Interchanging
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

limits and derivatives
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With a distribution, limits and (distributional) derivatives can always
 be interchanged.
 This is tremendously useful when talking about PDEs and convergence of
 approximations.
 In the distribution sense, the Fourier series can 
\emph on
always
\emph default
 be differentiated term-by-term, for example.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is easy to prove.
 Suppose that the distributions 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}\to f$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
 That is, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}\{\phi\}\to f\{\phi\}$
\end_inset

.
 Since this is true for 
\emph on
any
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)$
\end_inset

, it must be true for 
\begin_inset Formula $-\phi'(x)$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{n}'\{\phi\}=f_{n}\{-\phi'\}\to f\{-\phi'\}=f'\{\phi\}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $n\to\infty$
\end_inset

.
 Q.E.D.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Rules for distributions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the most part, in 18.303, we will cheat a bit.
 We will treat things as ordinary functions whenever we can, using the ordinary
 operations, and only switch to interpreting them as distributions when
 we run into difficulty (e.g.
 derivatives of discontinuities, etcetera).
 Since the rules for distribution operations are all defined to be consistent
 with those for functions in the case of regular distributions, this doesn't
 usually cause any trouble.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, it is good to define some of the important operations on distributions
 precisely.
 All you have to do is to explain what the operation does to test functions,
 usually defined by analogy with 
\begin_inset Formula $\int f(x)\phi(x)dx$
\end_inset

 for regular distributions.
 Here are a few of the most basic operations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
differentiation: 
\begin_inset Formula $f'\{\phi\}=f\{-\phi\}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
addition: 
\begin_inset Formula $(f_{1}+f_{2})\{\phi\}=f_{1}\{\phi\}+f_{2}\{\phi\}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
multiplication by smooth functions (including constants) 
\begin_inset Formula $s(x)$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $[s(x)\cdot f]\{\phi\}=f\{s(x)\phi(x)\}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
product rule for multiplication by smooth functions 
\begin_inset Formula $s(x)$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula $[s\cdot f]'\{\phi\}=[s\cdot f]\{-\phi'\}=f\{-s\phi'\}=f\{s'\phi-(s\phi)'\}=f\{s'\phi\}+f'\{s\phi\}=[s'\cdot f]\{\phi\}+[s\cdot f']\{\phi\}=[s'\cdot f+s\cdot f']\{\phi\}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
translation: 
\begin_inset Formula $[f(x-y)]\{\phi(x)\}=f\{\phi(x+y)\}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
scaling 
\begin_inset Formula $[f(\alpha x)]\{\phi(x)\}=\frac{1}{\alpha}f\{\phi(x/\alpha)\}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If you are not sure where these rules come from, just try plugging them
 into a regular distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $f\{\phi\}=\int f(x)\phi(x)dx$
\end_inset

, and you'll see that they work out in the ordinary way.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Problems with distributions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unfortunately, distributions are not a free lunch; they come with their
 own headaches.
 There are two major difficulties, one of which is surmountable and the
 other is not: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Boundary conditions: since distributions do not have values at individual
 points, it is not so easy to impose boundary conditions on the solutions
 if they are viewed as distributions—what does it mean to set 
\begin_inset Formula $u(0)=0$
\end_inset

? There are ways around this, but they are a bit cumbersome, especially
 in more than one dimension.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Multiplication: it is not generally meaningful to multiply distributions.
 The simplest example is the delta function: what would 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(x)^{2}$
\end_inset

 be? 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{\Delta x}(x)^{2}$
\end_inset

 is okay, but its limit as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x\to0$
\end_inset

 does not exist even as a distribution (the amplitude goes as 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\Delta x^{2}$
\end_inset

 while the integral goes as 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x$
\end_inset

, so it diverges).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For linear PDEs, lack of multiplication is not such a big problem, but it
 does mean that we need to be careful about Hilbert spaces: if we think
 of the solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)$
\end_inset

 as distributions, we have a problem because 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle u,u\rangle$
\end_inset

 may not be defined—the set of distributions does not form a Hilbert space.
 (Technically, we can make something called a 
\emph on
rigged Hilbert space
\emph default
 that includes distributions, but I don't want to go there.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The weak form of a PDE
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose we have a linear PDE 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}u=f$
\end_inset

.
 We want to allow 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 to be a delta function etcetera, but we still want to talk about boundary
 conditions, Hilbert spaces, and so on for 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

.
 There is a relatively simple compromise for linear PDEs, called the 
\series bold
weak form
\series default
 of the PDE or the 
\series bold
weak solution
\series default
.
 This concept can roughly be described as requiring 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}u=f$
\end_inset

 only in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

weak
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 sense of distributions (i.e., integrated against test functions, taking distribut
ional derivatives in the case of a 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 with discontinuities), but requiring 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 to be in a more restrictive class, e.g.
 regular distributions corresponding to functions satisfying the boundary
 conditions in the ordinary sense but having some continuity and differentiabili
ty so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle u,u\rangle$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle u,\hat{A}u\rangle$
\end_inset

 are finite (i.e., living in an appropriate Sobolev space).
 Even this definition gets rather technical very quickly, especially if
 you want to allow delta functions for 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 (in which case 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 can blow up at the point of the delta for dimensions 
\begin_inset Formula $>1$
\end_inset

).
 Nailing down precisely what spaces of functions and operators one is dealing
 with is where a lot of technical difficulty and obscurity arises in functional
 analysis.
 However, for practical engineering and science applications, we can get
 away with being a little careless in precisely how we define the function
 spaces because the weird counterexamples are usually obviously unphysical.
 The key insight of distributions is that what we care about is weak equality,
 not pointwise equality, and correspondingly we only need weak derivatives
 (integration by parts, or technically 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

bilinear forms
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Green's functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now that we have distributions, Green's functions are much easier to work
 with.
 Consider, for example, the Green's function 
\begin_inset Formula $G(x,x')$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}=-\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial x^{2}}$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,L]$
\end_inset

 with Dirichlet (zero) boundary conditions.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}u=f$
\end_inset

 is to be solved by 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)=\int G(x,x')f(x')dx'$
\end_inset

, then we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}u=\int[\hat{A}G(x,x')]f(x')dx'=f(x)$
\end_inset

, which is true if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{A}G(x,x')=\delta(x-x')
\]

\end_inset

and the integrals are re-interpreted as evaluating a distribution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What does this equation mean? For any 
\begin_inset Formula $x\neq x'$
\end_inset

 [or for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x')=0$
\end_inset

] we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}G(x,x')=0=-\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial x^{2}}G(x,x')$
\end_inset

, and this must mean that 
\begin_inset Formula $G(x,x')$
\end_inset

 is a straight line for 
\begin_inset Formula $x<x'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x>x'$
\end_inset

.
 To satisfy, the boundary conditions, this straight line must pass through
 zero at 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $G(x,x')$
\end_inset

 must look like 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha x$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x<x'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta(x-L)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x>x'$
\end_inset

 for some constants 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $G(x,x')$
\end_inset

 had better be continuous at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=x'$
\end_inset

, or otherwise we would get a delta function from the 
\emph on
first
\emph default
 derivative—hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\beta(x'-L)/x'$
\end_inset

.
 The first derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial}{\partial x}G(x,x')$
\end_inset

 then gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x<x'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x>x'$
\end_inset

.
 What about the next derivative? Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial}{\partial x}G(x,x')$
\end_inset

 is discontinuous, it doesn't have an ordinary second derivative at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=x'$
\end_inset

, but as a distribution it is no problem: 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial x^{2}}G(x,x')$
\end_inset

 is zero everywhere (the derivative of a constant) plus a delta function
 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(x-x')$
\end_inset

 multiplied by 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta-\alpha$
\end_inset

, the size of the jump.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $-\frac{\partial^{2}}{\partial x^{2}}G(x,x')=\hat{A}G=(\alpha-\beta)\delta(x-x')$
\end_inset

, and from above we must have 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha-\beta=1$
\end_inset

.
 Combined with the equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 from continuity of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

, we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=-x'/L$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=1-x'/L$
\end_inset

, exactly the same as our result from class (which we got by a more laborious
 method).
\end_layout

