\begin_layout Itemize
Delta functions are okay.
 You can employ their informal description without guilt because there is
 a rigorous definition to fall back on in case of doubt.
\begin_inset Separator latexpar
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
An 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

integral
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\delta(x-x')\phi(x)dx$
\end_inset

 just means 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x')$
\end_inset

.
 Integrals over finite domains 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{\Omega}\delta(x-x')\phi(x)$
\end_inset

 give 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x')$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $x'$
\end_inset

 is in the interior of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

 and 0 if 
\begin_inset Formula $x'$
\end_inset

 is outside 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

, but are undefined (or at least, more care is required) if 
\begin_inset Formula $x'$
\end_inset

 is on the boundary 
\begin_inset Formula $d\Omega$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
When in doubt about how to compute 
\begin_inset Formula $f'(x)$
\end_inset

, integrate by parts against a test function to see what 
\begin_inset Formula $\int f'(x)\phi(x)=-\int f(x)\phi'(x)$
\end_inset

 does (the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

weak
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

distributional
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 derivative).
\begin_inset Separator latexpar
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
A derivative of a discontinuity at 
\begin_inset Formula $x'$
\end_inset

 gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta(x-x')$
\end_inset

 multiplied by the size of the discontinuity [the difference 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x'^{+})-f(x'^{-})$
\end_inset

], plus the ordinary derivative everywhere else.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This also applies to differentiating functions like 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\sqrt{x}$
\end_inset

 that have finite integrals but whose classical derivatives have divergent
 integrals—applying the weak derivative instead produces a well-defined
 distribution.
 [For example, this procedure famously yields 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla^{2}\frac{1}{r}=-4\pi\delta(\vec{x})$
\end_inset

 in 3d.
 It also can lead to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Hadamard regularizations,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the famous Cauchy principal value, and other regularizations of apparently
 divergent integrals that are often presented in a mysterious fashion: a
 unique regularization arises because the integrand came from a distributional
 derivative or limit.]
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
All that matters in the distribution (weak) sense is the integral of a function
 times a smooth, localized test function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Anything that doesn't change such integrals 
\begin_inset Formula $\int f(x)\phi(x)$
\end_inset

, like finite values of 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 at isolated points, doesn't matter.
 (That is, whenever we use 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

=
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for functions we are almost always talking about 
\emph on
weak
\emph default
 equality.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Interchanging limits and derivatives is okay in the distribution sense.
 Differentiating Fourier series (and other expansions in infinite bases)
 term-by-term is okay.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In practice, we only ever need to solve PDEs in the distribution sense (a
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

weak
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 solution): integrating the left- and right-hand sides against any test
 functions must give the same number, with all derivatives taken in the
 weak sense.
\end_layout

